## Architecture guidance

- **Shell once, views many:** the shell is a layout; each view is routed content inside it.
- **Tables are components:** a generic `<DataTable>` with typed columns beats bespoke markup per table —
  and centralises the accessibility (scope, caption, keyboard).
- **State → attributes → variants:** drawer/row/loading states as data attributes styled by variants.
- **Density via tokens:** define a compact spacing scale token set; dashboards live or die on density.

<Callout type="insight" title="Dashboards expose whether your system actually scales">

Marketing sites are forgiving — lots of whitespace, few states. Dashboards are merciless: dozens of
components on one screen, every interactive state, real accessibility stakes (people *work* here all
day), and performance pressure from data volume. If your design system holds up here — consistent
density, accessible tables and forms by default, a shell that absorbs new views, dark mode that stays
readable on data-dense screens — then it's a real system, not a demo. This capstone is where the
architecture tier (Modules 9–11) proves itself under load. Build it well and you have undeniable
evidence of staff/principal-level capability.

</Callout>

## Acceptance criteria

- All views responsive and keyboard-navigable; focus visible and managed in overlays.
- Table is semantic (scope/caption), sortable and filterable, announced correctly.
- Forms validate accessibly with clear error association; loading/disabled states present.
- Light/dark contrast-safe at data density; tests + CI green; build prerenders where applicable.
